...John R. likedSee all activitySummary30 years of diverse business experience with a career path as VP, SVP, EVP, CFO, COO, CEO and board member, including serving as public company board as a board committee chairs of multi‐billion dollar publicly‐traded and privately‐held companies in the energy, transportation, manufacturing and education sectors.Experience includes a combination turnaround and restructuring, hands‐on operations, M&A and business development, financial engineering and strategic transformation in a wide variety of businesses with a strong track record of delivering financial and operational results, as well as top grading executive teams.ExperienceDirector Chairman of Audit & Compensation Committees NYSE:DITAMCON Distributing Company2003  –  Present (14 years)Greater Omaha AreaServing in leadership role on the board of directors of this NYSE traded distribution company, including Chairman of the audit committee and Chairman of the compensation committee.Led a special committee of the board that completely restructured the company by re‐focusing management on the core business and leading successful divestiture of non‐core business lines. These strategic direction changes led the business back to financial health and drove more than a 400% improvement in AMCON’s stock priceEVP for Business and Administrative AffairsKing's College2012  –  Present (5 years)Developed and lead the implementation of a college-wide strategy "March to Sustainability" focused on creating a continual process of creating new resources to stabilize and then grow our mission through enhancing the student experience. Key outcomes from the plan:Reengineering all major functions and rationalizing staffing levels across all areas of the college reducing the cost structure by 25% annually. Upgrading the management team in key areas leading to additional cost reductions and increased service levels. This reengineering effort created the first wave of new resources to stabilize the institution.Refinancing the capital structure five times in 48 months expanding capacity, lowering interest and debt service. This created the first wave of resources that could be invested in new programs and talent to improve the student experience. Redesigning the pricing model leading to significant increases in net tuition revenue creating a third wave of new resources that could be allocated to growth and improvement.New resources were used to overhaul the enrollment management process, rebranding to better position the college in its market and ultimately to implement new programs allowing the College to expand its market presence and diversify it's revenue base in a challenging market. These efforts generated additional resources to be reinvested in the next round of growth initiatives creating new programs including, engineering, nursing, hockey, track & field, expansion of our PA program and several others.In 48 month the March to Sustainability resulted in the complete corporatization of the institution. Key milestones include our largest freshman class ever, improving student profiles, rising student population, operating surpluses over 2% of revenue, an investment grade credit rating and repeatable processes to ensure our successes continue to be sustainable well into the future. These successes have now become the basis for a new capital campaign.Chairman of the Board of DirectorsNortheast Pennsylvania Education Consortium2012  –  Present (5 years)Scranton, Pennsylvania AreaNEPEC is a consortium committed to deliver value through partnering in today's competitive world. It's core mission is to drive cost savings for it's member institutions through key partnering relationships developed over the last decade. NEPEC has delivered millions of dollars in partnering saving to it members since its inception.Board of DirectorsLuzerne County Industrial Development Authority2016  –  Present (1 year)The Luzerne County Industrial Development Authority (“IDA”) is authorized to issue tax exempt bonds on behalf of eligible manufacturing,  501 C 3 non-profit organizations, and certain “exempt” issues such as water and sewer utility facilities. Under the programs eligible entities interested in expanding or locating in Luzerne County can finance  land, building, associated machinery and equipment through the issuance of tax-exempt or taxable bonds, and through authorized programs.Board Member Executive & Investment CommitteeLuzerne Foundation2015  –  Present (2 years)The Luzerne Foundation is a community foundation in NEPA that is philanthropic leader, a community resource and a financial steward. The Luzerne Foundation supports donors with their charitable giving, helping them invest strategically in causes they care about and in ways that make a difference in our community. However, unlike other organizations, a community foundation is focused on developing funds that will live on in perpetuity providing support to the community for generations to come.Borad Member TreasurerEducation Opportunity Center2013  –  Present (4 years)The Educational Opportunity Centers of Pennsylvania provides FREE services to encourage and assist adults, as well as high school students in target area schools who are interested in continuing their education. Funded through the United States Department of Education TRiO program, we focus on the low- income, first- generation student.  The Educational Opportunity Centers of Pennsylvania provides Financial Aid Assistance, help completing the FAFSA, the PHEAA, and guidance with college admission and career counseling. The Educational Opportunity Centers of Pennsylvania is staffed by a dedicated team of professionals who are experts in the field of post-secondary access, education and training.Board of DirectorsWyoming Valley Habitat for Humanity2016  –  Present (1 year)Wyoming Valley Habitat for Humanity is a non-profit organization that builds simple, decent homes to sell to families in need. We use volunteer labor and charitable gifts to ensure our homes are affordable to low income families in Wyoming Valley.Board MemberGreater Pittston Historical Society2015  –  Present (2 years)President & CEOEnergyCo/Optim Energy (a PNM Resources Company)2007  –  2012 (5 years)Dallas/Fort Worth AreaSpecifically recruited by PNM Resources to create a vision and build this start‐up ERCOT‐based power producer from a concept to a premier unregulated integrated energy platform. Produced annual gross revenues of over a billion dollars, while growing EBITDA from $10 million to over $64 million in less than three years, despite volatile power and gas, Results were achieved by continually reengineering the business over the five-year period to financial exit .Integrated and developed a 1,200 MW power plant fleet from the ground up with coal and gas plant availability in the top decile, and near‐perfect safety and environmental records.Created and designed the commercial function from scratch by installing a dynamic hedging strategy and strong fundamental market analysis to capture the extrinsic value of the genera􀆟ng fleet; installed a stringent risk management function to ensure earnings at risk and liquidity at risk are appropriately managed in relation to optimizing the value of the generation fleet.Focused Optim’s strategy on growing generation in the ERCOT Texas power market. Optimized the business through streamlining the generation fleet, adding new genera􀆟on with the construction of new assets and developing a systemic cost improvement process that streamlined the entire business platform. Drove a strategy to integrate the business with retail and completely restructure the capital structure. Completely restructured plant operations and capital maintence routines saving millions. Restructured fuel supply agreements and exploited alternative fuel options to drive millions out of the cost structure.Built a highly successful and cohesive executive management team from the ground up.Successfully lead an ownership transition.President & CEOCPG International2005  –  2007 (2 years)Created the strategic and tactical operations plan that evolved CPG into one of America’s premier building products companies, transforming it from a plastic sheet manufacturer to a highly engineered, high growth building products company with one of the best profitability profiles in the building products sector. The strategy created an exit that allowed a business acquired for $300 million to be sold for $1.5 billion.From 2005‐2007, sales grew 62% in one of the most difficult residential building markets in recent times. EBITDA, over the same time period, doubled from $35 million to $70 million, and EBITDA margin improved from 19% to 22%. This strong financial and operational performance enabled CPG to fund and successfully integrate two major acquisitions (ProCell Decking Systems and Santana products) while significantly improving credit metrics.Developed a leadership team to drive necessary organizational change; consolidated four poorly resourced business units into two high performing, fully resourced businesses. Installed a financial and technology team to support taking the company public; developed a strategic capacity plan and engineered an organizational structure to support the high growth of the business.Instituted LEAN manufacturing and 5S techniques to streamline and organize operations, improve throughput capabilities, drive production accuracy and reduce costs. Drove sales channel, brand and pricing strategies that supported the organization through the catastrophic impacts of hurricanes Katrina and Rita on the company’s raw material resources.SVP & CFOPNM Resources1999  –  2005 (6 years)Albuquerque, New Mexico AreaLead the creation of PNMR’s strategic mission of “Building America’s Best Merchant Utility” and leveraging that mission into a strategy that transformed the company into one of America’s best performing utilities.Facilitated this transformation by identifying, recruiting and developing key people and support processes to drive dramatic change in the organization. This people and process focus was combined with a disciplined growth strategy that included corporate and asset acquisitions as well as a focus on re‐engineering PNMR’s core business.Results included: growing PNMR from just under $1 billion revenue to just under $3 billion; and growing market capitalization from $500 million to $2 billion by increasing per share equity values over 100% in less than 5 years.Led PNMR corporate development resulting in the addition of several well placed, low cost, high profit, unregulated genera􀆟ng assets in the southwest and the highly successful acquisition of TNP Enterprises, a Texas‐based utility.Developed a capital structure restructuring plan that included the refinancing of $1.5 billion in high cost debt, the brokering of a $1.2 billion revolving credit facility, issuing $1 billion in common equity and convertible equity securities resulting in a two notch credit upgrade to BBB and $14 million in annual interest savings in less than four years.Re‐engineered PNMR’s investor relations program, transforming a li􀆩le known regional utility into one of the most respected on Wall Street, and more than doubling the institutional investor base.Managed corporate development, strategy, corporate planning, treasury, investor relations, the controllership, information technologies, internal audit, risk management, business reengineering and supply chain.Led the finance team to a fully successful SOX implementation.Served as a member of the Executive Management Committee (a group of eight senior officers that determined strategy and policy for the corpora􀆟on.)Director of Financial ReportingUnion Pacific1991  –  1999 (8 years)Greater Omaha AreaManagerLutron Electronics1989  –  1991 (2 years)Allentown, Pennsylvania AreaSenior AuditorPricewaterhouseCoopers1985  –  1989 (4 years)Greater Philadelphia AreaSkillsEnergyCommod